Long Short Equities

Data Wrangling

# For companies
fund <- subset(fundlst, fundlst$Main.Investment.Strategy == 'Long Short Equities')
fundname <- fund$Fund.Name
fund.ret <- subset(fundret, fundret$Fund.Name %in% fundname)  # only 3 funds have returns
col_name <- colnames(fund.ret)
date <- col_name[c(-1, -2, -3)]
co.ret = t(fund.ret[,4:ncol(fund.ret)] / 100)
co.ret.xts = xts(co.ret, as.yearmon(date,'%b.%y'))
colnames(co.ret.xts) <- c('Redwood','Renaissance','SEG')
co.ret.xts <- co.ret.xts[index(co.ret.xts) >= as.yearmon('Jan 1998'),]
# For Indices
index.dt <- dplyr::select(data, contains(c("Date", "Equity")))
index.xts = xts(index.dt, as.yearmon(index.dt$Date,'%b.%y'))
colnames(index.xts) <- c('Date', 'Value', 'Momentum', 'Carry', 'Defensive', 'Multi-Style', 'Market')
index.xts <- index.xts[index.xts$Date >= "1998-01-30"]
index.xts <- index.xts[, 2:7]

storage.mode(index.xts) <- "numeric"

Observation

For Companies

  1. Redwood is much volatile compared to Renaissance and SEG. The Volatility plot validate this conclusion.
  2. Based on the fundamental investment theory, the higher the volatility, the higher the returns we can anticipate. So Redwood should provide better returns to compensate its high volatility. However, based on the culmulative return analysis, we observe that it has underperformed by both SEG and Renaissance from 1998 and 2007 respectively. Currently the return of Renaissance is the double of Redwood.
  3. Beside returns, we delve into more metrics. The overall Sharpe ratio of Redwood is the lowest among the three, while SEG is the highest. However, it doesnt account for the COVID effect on the market. If we only observe the period for both SEG and Renaissance operate, we can find the Sharpe ratio of these two companies are quite similar.
  4. If we observe Sharpe ratio by rolling basis, we can know that Redwood is extremely unstable with highest 6-7% and lowest -6% per month. Renaissance and SEG are mostly bounded between +2% and -2% per month.
  5. As for max drawdown, three companies suffered severely from 2008 financial crisis. The worst drawdown for the three all happened in this period. If we look at the COVID pandemic, we can find that the drawdown for Renaissance is not a lot less severe compared to the financial crisis, while the drawdown for Redwood is less severe compared to the financial crisis.
  6. Another observation is that during the COVID period, Redwoods performance bounced back quicker than Renaissances, showing its instability.

For Indices

  1. Market is the most volatile one, followed by the Momentum.
  2. Based on the cumulative return analysis, the rank is Market > Momentum > Defensive > Multi-Style > Value > Carry, which aligns with the investment theory that the higher the volatility, the higher the return we can expect. The reason behind is that for the previous few years, the stock market soared a lot, which was beneficial for both Market and Momentum.
  3. Another implication from the cumulative return is that we can validate the three Hedge Funds indeed beat the indices.
  4. As for Sharpe ratio, Market is the most volatile, but is not quite different from others in most years. Another interesting thing I observed is that the Value and Market seem to have counter effect as their performance showed quite opposite to each other.
  5. As for max drawdown, different indices show quite different patterns.
  • Value starts the downward trend after 2008 financial crisis.
  • Momentum shows oscillatory pattern because of the core idea of the momentum strategy.
  • Carry slumped a lot from 2015 and has not yet bounced back.
  • Defensive also shows oscillatory throughout past few years.
  • Multi-Style is relatively stable as it incorporates various kinds of companies to reduce its risks.
  • Market is greatly influenced by the market condition. Whenever there is a big trouble in the market, it suffers the most.

Model: Redwood Return(m) = 0.006 + 0.198 * Equity_Indices_Market(m-1)

From the pairwise evaluation we can find that the correlation between Redwoods returns and all the variables is small. Only the Market is a little bit related to it (but only 0.176). As a result, the backward selection gives a result of simple linear model which only contains Market as the variable.

The reasons behind it may be the investment focus of Redwood. It mainly invests in financial, industrial, and consumer discretionary sector. All these three are quite easily affected by the market condition.
